08166nam a22009855i 9780812297164DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122971647 a10.9783/97808122971642doi  a(DE-B1597)563157  a(OCoLC)1163552060  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHT165.5b.M33 2020 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a307.1/21622300aLife Among Urban Planners :bPractice, Professionalism, and Expertise in the Making of the City /ced. by Jennifer Mack, Michael Herzfeld. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b15 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe City in the Twenty-First Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Living Life Among Planners -- tPART I. Social and Cultural Contexts of Planning -- t1. Shaping Cultural Space: Reflections on the Politics and Cosmology of Urbanism -- t2. Why Planners Need Anthropologists -- t3. Redesigning the Republic? Public Gardens, Participatory Design, and Citizenship in Immigrant Paris -- tPART II. Grand Plans and Their Discontents -- t4. Zoning as Default: The Politics of Foreign- Sponsored Urban Planning in Siem Reap, Cambodia -- t5. An Anatomy of Failure: Planning After the Fact in Contemporary Bogotá, Colombia -- t6. A “Zoning Tombola”: Informal Planning in Niamey, Niger -- t7. Breaking the Rules, Making the Ruler: Syriac Homes and the Limits of Swedish Planning -- tPART III. Resituating a “Universal” Praxis -- t8. The Scales of Justice: Region, Rights, and Responsibility in St. Louis, Missouri -- t9. Power without the Mustache: Urban Quality as Planning Practice in Post- Industrial Barcelona -- t10. The Games We Play: What Is Participation in Urban Planning? Insights from Warsaw -- t11. From the Real to the Virtual: A Swedish Solution for “Universal” Sustainable Development in Hammarby Sjöstad, Stockholm -- tAfterword: The Problem of the Present in Anthropology and Urban Planning -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA collection of ethnographic case studies of urban planners and their practicesUrban planners project the future of cities. As experts, they draft visions of places and times that do not yet exist, prescribing the tools to be used to achieve those visions. Their choices can determine how a city will merge its public transit and automobile traffic or how it will meet a demand for thousands of new dwelling units as quickly and with as little avoidable damage as possible. Life Among Urban Planners considers planning professionals in relation to the social contexts in which they operate: the planning office, the construction site, and even in the confrontations with thos eaffected by their work. What roles do planners have in shaping the daily practices of urban life? How do they employ, manipulate, and alter their expertise to meet the demands asked of them? The essays in this volume emphasize planners' cultural values and personal assumptions and critically examine what their persistent commitment to thinking about the future means for the ways in which people live in the present and preserve the past.Life Among Urban Planners explores the practices and politics of professional city-making in a wide selection of geographical areas spanning five continents. Cases include but are not limited to Bangkok, Bogotá, Chicago, Naimey, Rome, Siem Reap, Stockholm, and Warsaw. Examining the issues raised around questions of expertise, participation, and the tension between market and state forces, contributors demonstrate how certain planning practices accentuate their specific relationship to a place while others are represented to a global audience as potentially universal solutions. In presenting detailed and intimate portraits of the everyday lives of planners, the volume offers key insights into how the city interacts with the world.Contributors: Margaret Crawford, Adèle Esposito, Trevor Goldsmith, Mark Graham, Michael Herzfeld, James Holston, Gabriella Körling, Jennifer Mack, Andrew Newman, Lissa Nordin, Bruce O'Neill, Kevin Lewis O'Neill, Federico Pérez, Monika Sznel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCity planners. 0aCity planningxSocial aspects. 0aCity planning. 0aUrban anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aGeneral.  aSocial Science.  aUrban Studies.1 aCrawford, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsposito Andujar, Adèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldsmith, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzfeld, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzfeld, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHolston, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKörling, Gabriella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMack, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMack, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNewman, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordin, Lissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’neill, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’neill, Kevin Lewis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPérez, Federico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSznel, Monika, econtrib